INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '4fb253b1-b15d-4fc9-91ac-9fcd8bfaca6c',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Vite's Dual Engine: Why Dev and Prod Feel Different$escape$,
  $escape$Vite runs two completely different build pipelines depending on environment — and understanding the split prevents production surprises.

In dev, Vite skips bundling entirely. It serves source files as native ES modules directly to the browser, letting the browser's module graph drive what gets loaded. Vite only transforms files on request, making cold starts near-instant regardless of project size. But bare imports like `import _ from 'lodash-es'` would trigger hundreds of network requests — so Vite uses esbuild to pre-bundle node_modules into single ESM files, cached in `node_modules/.vite/deps`.

In prod, esbuild hands off to Rollup. Rollup's superior tree-shaking, code-splitting, and chunk optimization make it the right tool for shipping. This is why you configure `build.rollupOptions` — not an esbuild equivalent — for output chunking, externals, and library mode.

The gap matters: a CJS package that esbuild pre-bundles fine in dev may fail Rollup's ESM-strict prod build. Use `vite build --mode development` to catch these mismatches early, or inspect pre-bundle output via `vite --debug` to see exactly what esbuild resolved.$escape$,
  $escape$// vite.config.ts
export default defineConfig({
  optimizeDeps: {
    // Force-include a package esbuild might miss during pre-bundling
    include: ['lodash-es'],
    // Exclude packages that must stay unbundled in dev
    exclude: ['@my-org/local-pkg'],
  },
  build: {
    rollupOptions: {
      output: {
        // Rollup-only: split vendor chunks in prod
        manualChunks: (id) =>
          id.includes('node_modules') ? 'vendor' : undefined,
      },
    },
  },
});$escape$,
